Some have even suggested that people in the commissioner's office have been winking at one another while they make public pronouncements against steroid use. From my perspective, these critics are jumping to unfair conclusions. Commissioner Bud Selig and Major League Baseball have taken a lot of heat over the last several months for their supposed failure to grapple forthrightly with the sport's steroid problem. Before the mid-1990s, the substances of choice in the clubhouse were amphetamines and recreational drugs. At the time, many anabolic steroids were illegal if purchased without a prescription. 